Class INTnull

java.lang.Object
  org.hl7.types.impl.ANYimpl
      org.hl7.types.impl.ORDimpl
          org.hl7.types.impl.INTnull
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Comparable<ORD>, ANY, INT, Numeric, ORD, QTY, QTY.diff
Direct Known Subclasses:
INTninf, INTpinf
public class INTnull
extends ORDimpl
implements INT, Numeric

Minimal implementation of INT as a model we can use for all other type. This one is only used to convey NULL values. Again, we have static values of it, so we don't create so many objects in a running program.

public BL lessOrEqual(ORD x)
Description copied from interface: ORD
An ordering relation that tests whether this ordinal is less or equal to that ordinal. IMPLEMENTATION NOTE: as a convention, this should be the one basic ordering relation that should be implemented for every implementation. The other comparison relations can be derived from this one and the equality property (defined for all data values, ANY).

plus

public QTY plus(QTY.diff x)
Description copied from interface: QTY
A new quantity of the kind of this quantity, that linearly translated by a ratio-quantity expressing the difference between two values of the kind of this quantity. Note that plus as can be defined in QTY alone is not commutative. One *could* make it commutative by defining QTY diff.plus(QTY) but that cannot be specified here.

Specified by:
plus in interface QTY

Description copied from interface: QTY
The difference between two quantities as a ratio-scale quantity. This is the most fundamental operation of difference- scale quantities, i.e., that between every two values of that quantity, there is a difference.

Specified by:
minus in interface QTY

minus

public INT minus(QTY.diff x)
Description copied from interface: QTY
A short hand for QTY.plus(that.negated()); ISSUE: We are using the same operation name and the difference in signature is subtle because an diff is a QTY. For all ratio-quantities these two forms of minus(QTY) and minus(diff) are in fact the same. Having the same name is nice on the one hand, but may be confusing.

Specified by:
minus in interface QTY
